7FsIx4kAmqH8j4h_OaLDjAceQUCFRt3WCUtW0BrNLTTa5lVK1fKdN6Hu8jOqYSKpybA78V4fHncx71WB7LfndpBA2X2wkCxRgpuSS3odK084oai9oCzlfoqshpFdiZRZ4kbLxndSp8g5zdqu_xys0hRh3V-vy6nlGh99GqtLXloVZ2m5aXMc9hllUV8jRLMehdzFlSYhSD79odd5hZswa6KoZlIVEhsPZIwYT4Xpqvz6igz86onr2HK7O6eE09_T1ui6fCIJEUBoaitnCjE2b1pctS0UEFvZSc=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test resources inclusion**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether test resources need to be included under Native Image. It seems like Gradle may automatically generate a resource configuration, including any test resources by default? If I add files, does the plugin take care of that? I should avoid modifying `src/test/resources/META-INF/native-image`, but it might be okay to add image files to `src/test/resources/images/*.gif`. Ultimately, I need to ensure that resources are available while preventing any null pointer exceptions from dynamic resource calls in the library.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating resource inclusion**\\n\\nI’m looking at adding resources for tests by including files under `src/test/resources`, which currently seems empty. While adding resource files doesn’t modify the native-image config, it raises a question about expected active class resources. I’m considering including 14 GIF files, and I wonder if it’s acceptable to duplicate files. \\n\\nI’ll explore creating a transparent GIF and check whether I should write these as binary or if text tools can manage it. I'll also look into using Python for file operations and ensuring the classloader can find the necessary resources.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining Native Image configuration**\\n\\nI need to consider that reflection calls in Native Image require specific configuration, and I wonder about the role of the agent during metadata generation. If the test resources are included by the native plugin, that’s helpful, but I’m also contemplating whether I need to include resources if they're already in the jar. \\n\\nI'm thinking about avoiding reflection by using a different package but realize that dynamic reflection could be unsupported without the right config. I need to check if the agent generated the reflection metadata when executing tests on the JVM first. It seems like the classloader's resource calls might integrate external data into metadata, which is a good approach since we're not modifying the config.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning test implementation**\\n\\nI think I need a user-code filter that excludes the test package but includes the library. This way, the agent can successfully record resource calls from the library, which seems like a solid approach. I’m feeling good about this direction. Now, it's time to write the test. I want to make sure I'm thorough so that I capture any potential issues. Let's get started on that!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kSm9CKcuAHHWcCyFJ0qu3WX9|fc_08953fcd1000c0ed0169fa71996428819db94ad9a62db6dee8", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.scalatest/scalatest-core_3/3.2.19/src/test/scala/org_scalatest/scalatest_core_3/IconEmbellishedListCellRendererInnerIconsTest.scala", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_scalatest.scalatest_core_3\n\nimport java.lang.reflect.Constructor\nimport java.lang.reflect.Method\n\nimport javax.swing.ImageIcon\n\nimport org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\n\nclass IconEmbellishedListCellRendererInnerIconsTest {\n\n  @Test\n  def initializesEveryRendererIconResource(): Unit = {\n    val rendererClass: Class[?] = Class.forName(\"org.scalatest.tools.IconEmbellishedListCellRenderer\")\n    val renderer: Object = rendererClass.getConstructor().newInstance().asInstanceOf[Object]\n    val iconsClass: Class[?] = Class.forName(\"org.scalatest.tools.IconEmbellishedListCellRenderer$Icons$\")\n    val iconsConstructor: Constructor[?] = iconsClass.getConstructor(rendererClass)\n    val icons: Object = iconsConstructor.newInstance(renderer).asInstanceOf[Object]\n\n    val iconResources: Map[String, String] = Map(\n      \"testStartingIcon\" -> \"purpledot.gif\",\n      \"testSucceededIcon\" -> \"greendot.gif\",\n      \"testFailedIcon\" -> \"reddot.gif\",\n      \"infoProvidedIcon\" -> \"bluedot.gif\",\n      \"runStartingIcon\" -> \"graydot.gif\",\n      \"suiteStartingIcon\" -> \"cyandot.gif\",\n      \"testIgnoredIcon\" -> \"yellowdot.gif\",\n      \"testStartingSelIcon\" -> \"purpledotsel.gif\",\n      \"testSucceededSelIcon\" -> \"greendotsel.gif\",\n      \"testFailedSelIcon\" -> \"reddotsel.gif\",\n      \"infoProvidedSelIcon\" -> \"bluedotsel.gif\",\n      \"runStartingSelIcon\" -> \"graydotsel.gif\",\n      \"suiteStartingSelIcon\" -> \"cyandotsel.gif\",\n      \"testIgnoredSelIcon\" -> \"yellowdotsel.gif\"\n    )\n\n    iconResources.foreach { case (methodName: String, resourceName: String) =>\n      val method: Method = iconsClass.getMethod(methodName)\n      val icon: ImageIcon = method.invoke(icons).asInstanceOf[ImageIcon]\n\n      assertThat(icon.getDescription()).endsWith(s\"images/$resourceName\")\n      assertThat(icon.getIconWidth()).isGreaterThan(0)\n      assertThat(icon.getIconHeight()).isGreaterThan(0)\n    }\n  }\n}\n"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 416, "output": 2122, "cacheRead": 28672, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 31210, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778020738408, "responseId": "resp_08953fcd1000c0ed0169fa7182f590819d9df852d31db8f999"}}
