d, keeping everything organized without reflection issues. Would adding Java conflict with the Gradle Scala plugin?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java helper usage**\\n\\nI'm considering whether using a Java helper counts as a \\\"test file.\\\" Reviewers might not like it, and using direct reflection could be against the rules. The developer emphasized avoiding direct reflection in tests unless public APIs require it. Using a Java helper sidesteps reflection but relies on a private class at compile time. It's okay to keep tests outside library packages, so I'll create a package-private helper under `src/test/java`. I need to make sure this doesn't violate mapping between report classes and test class files, and check if javac syntax supports that format.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java and Scala integration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether the source compiler might refuse the import due to the binary name having a `$`. This could be a potential issue because the `IconEmbellishedListCellRenderer` class is public in bytecode but has a private Scala signature, which javac will ignore — good to know! It might be better to replace Scala test reflections with a Java helper. I'll need Java for that. The Scala test file must still include assertions. Should the Java helper return a `Map` to eliminate Scala-Java collection conversions or perhaps use a static method like `loadIcon(String accessor)` instead?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java and Scala integration**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether methods could be public to simplify things, or if a nested class should be package-private. I wonder if the method return type is accessible. I need to import library classes in Java and question if Java will compile if I import private Scala classes directly. This might help avoid reflection and keep direct class references, which is important for the Native Image. I plan to edit the Scala test to remove 